<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-18T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="949" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d949">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1307: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-18T17:00:00-04:00">July 18, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>237. Legation’s 417, July 11, 4 p.m. Will you instruct the Consulates
                            General at Canton and Hong Kong to report through the Legation by mail
                            or by telegraph important instances of arms, munitions, and airplanes,
                            whether military or commercial, being shipped from the United States or
                            from other foreign countries to the Cantonese authorities; and likewise
                            to report cases of commercial airplanes which have been found in use for
                            military purposes.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
